Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. Navigation guard with confirmation dialog (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`)

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
            .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                           "Discard your changes?",
                           "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" — cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### 3. ViewModel back command (triggers the same guard)

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Back()
    {
        // This fires OnNavigating, so the guard above runs automatically
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async; without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops navigation when the user picks "Stay".
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` triggers `GoToAsync("..")`, which is a `Pop` — so the same `OnNavigating` guard catches both the custom button and the system back gesture.
